column10: str
column11: str
column12: str

column10: Summon your cherry bomb minion─a miniature recreation of a voidsent bomb, created via the thaumaturgical rendering of umbrally charged aetherial energy. Guaranteed never to self-destruct, or your gil back.
column11: To maintain the white-hot temperatures within their cores, bombs will feed upon almost any combustible material, including wood, charcoal, ceruleum, fire crystals, even dragon peppers.
column12:
Brilliant bombs─
breathtaking,
beautiful, brilliant!
  - Ba Go

column10: Summon your mammet #001 minion─a fully operational clockwork puppet built in a joint effort by the Alchemists' and Goldsmiths' Guilds.
column11: The standard frill-free #001 model is not only the best-selling mammet on the market, but is the blueprint on which all other clockwork servitors are based.
column12:
Mammets can't
even taste food!
  - Serendipity

column10: Summon your wayward hatchling minion. Until he finds his real mother, you'll have to suffice.
column11:
Even if this orphaned avian were to stumble across his birth parent, chances are he would not even blink an eye, for it is well documented that immediately after hatching, chocobos recognize the first thing they see as their mother─that being
you.
column12:
Whoa, whoa, whoa!
Hooold your chocobos.
  - Buscarron

column10: Summon your Cait Sith doll. The ever-extended tail helps the kitten keep her balance.
column11: The clockwork rendition of an enigmatic cat spirit from the pages of Midlander mythology, Goldsmiths' Guild guildmaster Serendipity crafted this lifelike figurine to bring joy to those children who were orphaned in the Calamity.
column12:
What may be a few to
you was everything to
those who died...
  - Cait Sith

column10: Summon your baby behemoth. We can only hope his mother doesn't come looking for him.
column11:
Obtainable in Ul'dah's Sapphire Avenue Exchange for a fistful of coin and a smile, the pedigree of this baby beast is questionable at best. While displaying many behemoth-like features─a sleek violet hide, hungry eyes, and two polished
horns─its squealing is not
unlike a boar at slaughter.
column12:
Disaster follows the man
like a behemoth chasing
a butterfly.
  - Chechezan

column10: Summon your mammet #003L minion─a fully operational clockwork puppet built for the Maelstrom.
column11: Designed to be a standard-bearer in Maelstrom company parades, these hand-crafted automatons were soon decommissioned due to the fact that their small stature ensured that no one could see the flags they carried.
column12:
Feelings! Maybe she just
doesn't feel like part of
the team!?
  - Wedge

column10: Summon your mammet #003G minion─a fully operational clockwork puppet built for the Order of the Twin Adder.
column11: Designed to be a standard-bearer in Order of the Twin Adder company parades, these hand-crafted automatons were soon decommissioned due to the fact that their small stature ensured that no one could see the flags they carried.
column12:
Feelings! Maybe she just
doesn't feel like part of
the team!?
  - Wedge

column10: Summon your mammet #003U minion─a fully operational clockwork puppet built for the Immortal Flames.
column11: Designed to be a standard-bearer in Immortal Flames company parades, these hand-crafted automatons were soon decommissioned due to the fact that their small stature ensured that no one could see the flags they carried.
column12:
Feelings! Maybe she just
doesn't feel like part of
the team!?
  - Wedge

column10: Summon your storm hatchling minion. Not more than a fortnight out of the shell, but his blood already runs Maelstrom red. Till sea swallows all!
column11: Raised by a storm private from an egg found abandoned in the company stables he was charged with cleaning, this adorable fledgling is a symbol of new beginnings for the mighty Maelstrom.
column12:
Chocobo dander can
be a mite ripe.
  - Chocobokeep

column10: Summon your serpent hatchling minion. Not more than a fortnight out of the shell, but his blood already runs Twin Adder yellow.
column11: Raised by a serpent private from an egg found abandoned in the company stables he was charged with cleaning, this adorable fledgling is a symbol of new beginnings for the Order of the Twin Adder.
column12:
Chocobo dander can
be a mite ripe.
  - Chocobokeep

column10: Summon your flame hatchling minion. Not more than a fortnight out of the shell, but his blood already runs Immortal Flames black.
column11: Raised by a flame private from an egg found abandoned in the company stables he was charged with cleaning, this adorable fledgling is a symbol of new beginnings for the Immortal Flames.
column12:
Chocobo dander can
be a mite ripe.
  - Chocobokeep

column10: Summon your morbol seedling minion...if you think you can stand his breath.
column11:
It is in fashion amongst wealthy Ul'dahn merchants and nobles to bring morbol seedlings to banquets, so that the upper crust might inhale the seedkin's “boot-like” bad breath to induce vomiting, allowing them to engorge themselves for the
duration of the gatherings.
column12:
Did a morbol just empty
its innards? I feel ill...
  - Imperial Soldier

column10: Summon your tiny rat minion. He may infest your granaries, and he may carry the plague, but he's <Emphasis>simply too adorable</Emphasis> to condemn to the life-ending jaws of a metal trap.
column11: It was only recently that an enterprising merchant from the Emerald Exchange in Ul'dah was tossed into the sultanate's oubliettes for fluffing the tails of rats caught on Pearl Avenue and selling prettied pests to tourists as “tiny squirrels.”
column12:
Pray waste no time
chasing rats.
  - Nanamo Ul Namo

column10: Summon your baby bun minion. Tastes great on salads and in stews.
column11:
For those wondering on the ill effects of inhaling spores released by common funguars, according to the <Emphasis>Encyclopedia Eorzea</Emphasis> (third edition), funguar spores “befoul the body's humours and claim control of an individual's very soul,
rendering them a mindless
thrall.”
column12:
You mushroom-headed,
spindly-legged, spore-
spewing abominations!
  - Gabineaux

column10: Summon your chigoe larva minion. This tiny vilekin takes the blood pact with his master <Emphasis>very</Emphasis> seriously.
column11: Chirurgeons of the fallen city of Gelmorra once used chigoes to leech the dark humours of the infirm until it was realized the patients were contracting additional maladies as a result of the treatment.
column12:
What am I going to do
with a pile of dead vilekin?
  - Waltheof

column10: Summon your bluebird minion. Known to retroactively bring good fortune to those who have already experienced good fortune.
column11:
Fortunate to hatch before being eaten by lizards. Unfortunate to fall from its nest before learning to fly. Fortunate to land in an empty treasure coffer. Unfortunate to still be in said coffer as it is filled with booty and locked up again.
Fortunate to be
plundered...by you.
column12:
The disbelieving cries
of our foe will be as
the sweetest birdsong.
  - Yadovv Gah

column10: Summon your wide-eyed fawn minion. His mother was either lost in a terrible hunting accident...or perhaps is just lost.
column11:
An easy target for Eorzea's carnivorous fauna, antelopes must use every advantage they have to remain free from death's dripping jaws. One of those is the remarkable ability to run mere minutes from birth. Unfortunately, that
trait did not save this
specimen from capture.
column12:
When making an offering
of antelope innards, it is
proper they are still warm.
  - Common Knowledge

column10: Summon your infant imp minion. Hopes that one day, he will rule the seven hells. But for now, your backside will do.
column11:
Scholars believe there are three ways in which voidsent can make the journey from their realm to ours─tearing a hole in the aether on their side, having a hole torn for them on our side, or stumbling into a randomly occurring
hole, the latter being the
most common for imps.
column12:
This bastard's got
some nasty spells!
  - Stalwart Swordsman

column10: Summon your coeurl kitten minion. It will still be several summers before his trademark whiskers grow out.
column11:
Coeurls are extremely proud and defiant creatures, even when young. Faced with insurmountable odds, a coeurl will rarely shy away from a fight, choosing rather to perish in combat than run. This characteristic keeps coeurl numbers low,
but ensures the strength
of those who survive.
column12:
Coeurl got your tongue?
  - Wilred

column10: Summon your black coeurl minion. Beware, for if one should cross your path, you will experience seven years of...AWWWWWW.
column11:
To the untrained eye, this coeurl appears to be of an entirely new species, when in fact the only thing separating him from his mottled brethren is that his spots are so large, they overlap with one another, rendering him completely
black.
column12:
Look what the
coeurl dragged in.
  - Momodi

column10: Summon your wind-up gentleman minion. If “clockwork Hildibrand” doesn't quite roll off the tongue, both “minion of enquiry” and “mammet extraordinaire” are acceptable alternatives.
column11:
Though he has once more taken to the heavens in a selfless act of sacrifice, Inspector Hildibrand lives on in the hearts of all whose lives he touched with his inimitable brand of gallantry, perception, and panache. Wind him up and
let him follow you as
only a Manderville can.
column12:
I have peeled away the
foul scab of uncertainty
to reveal the truth within!
  - Hildibrand

column10: Summon your gravel golem minion. Only you stand between it and a hard place.
column11:
Mage-controlled golems were in such wide use by the end of the Fifth Astral Era that entire battles were waged by armies comprised of nothing but the lifeless soulkin. This recreation, however, is nothing but a standard model #001
mammet outfitted with
simple gravel plating.
column12:
Gummice pollums? I fear
I'm not familiar with them.
  - Yhom Epocan

column10: Summon your wind-up tonberry minion. Now with 100% less rancor.
column11: While merely a clockwork toy crafted to resemble the twisted survivors of Nym, owners of similar creations claim waking to find their wind-up tonberries propped upon their chests, wooden knives pressed firmly against their throats.
column12:
I came expectin' to fight
one tonberry, not a whole
bloody mess of 'em.
  - Soft Marauder

column10: Summon your tiny tortoise minion. Will not carry you to an underwater kingdom if you ride on its back.
column11: Hatched from an egg laid in the ivory sands of La Noscea's Salt Strand, if lucky, this baby adamantoise may live to see as many as ten score summers...that is, if it does not accidentally launch itself off a cliff with its constant spinning.
column12:
What is that foul stench!?
It's like the inside of an
adamantoise's arse!
  -  Wood Wailer Sentry

column10: Summon your baby raptor minion. Luckily for you, his teeth haven't all grown in...yet.
column11:
Taking a hint from goblin merchants who raise raptors to serve as beasts of burden, a shopkeep from the village of Boughbury has begun hatching raptor eggs of his own (stolen from nearby nests). One can only hope the mother raptors
are not as clever as the
shopkeep thinks <Emphasis>he</Emphasis> is.
column12:
By the gods...
This raptor is sublime!
  - Nonopesa

column10: Summon your baby bat minion. Has yet to acquire a taste for blood.
column11: Nonoroon, resident junkmonger at Memeroon's Trading Post, came up with the idea for capturing and selling baby bats one day while raiding caves for bat eggs...of which he could not find any.
column12:
Even ate a wing off one
afore I made up my mind
to climb down the wall.
  - Ahldfoet

column10: Summon your tiny bulb minion. Some questions, such as why this bulb can walk, are best left unanswered.
column11:
To answer the question, “why can this bulb walk,” one must trace the seedkin's evolution back thousands of generations. Since this guide lacks the space to do so, let us simply say it has something to do with seeking sunlight under the eternal
darkness of the Black
Shroud's thick canopy.
column12:
Each sapling is another
glimpse into the wonder
of the world around us.
  - Fufucha

column10: Summon your dust bunny minion. Despite the striking similarities, spriggans are not related to rabbits. But they have been known to eat them.
column11:
It is not fully known why spriggans hoard precious rocks and minerals, though scholars would have us believe that it is the rocks and minerals which are hoarding the spriggans, hence the creatures' scientific classification as
soulkin.
column12:
Between the four of us,
surely we can outsmart
a few rogue spriggans.
  - Augustiniel

column10: Summon your wind-up dullahan minion. Warning: may contain sharp parts.
column11:
Voidsent dullahan are, in fact, shapeless entities who must first inhabit an inanimate host (such as a suit of armor) before gaining the ability to exert force upon the physical plane in which we reside. Luckily, the only things inhabiting this
wind-up contraption are
manifold gears and rods.
column12:
Pray retrieve the gift ere
it is crushed beneath the
iron feet of the dullahans!
  - G'raha Tia

column10: Summon your gigantpole minion. Yes, it can survive for hours on end without any water, and yes, it can fly. Your argument is invalid.
column11:
Over countless generations, the gigantoads of Thanalan have adapted to the arid climes by taking on traits not seen in their cousins to the north, such as thick membranes to keep their skin hydrated out of water, and a set of extra fins
which act as wings to
propel them over land.
column12:
These toads are huge,
which means they have
huge guts.
  - Hamon

column10: Summon your pudgy puk minion. Don't ask what it has eaten to grow so plump.
column11: Fattened from birth to be a succulent snack for the sadistic Steropes, this fledgling puk's excess baggage ensures that even if he attempts to flee, he will not be getting that far.
column12:
Ul'dah ain't more'n a
sand-crusted pile o' puk
dung bakin' in th' desert.
  - Baderon Tenfingers

column10: Summon your buffalo calf minion. Milk-fed until tender and juicy. Not that anyone would <Emphasis>ever</Emphasis> think of eating him.
column11:
When the Scions of the Seventh Dawn began clearing out the Waking Sands in preparation for the move to Revenant's Toll, this wide-eyed calf was discovered hiding in a disused linen closet. Though an inquiry was made by the Antecedent
herself, it is still not known
who was keeping the beast.
column12:
I made the grievous error
of visiting a great buffalo
with a handsaw.
  - Godbert

column10: Summon your cactuar cutting minion. Take care not to suffer 1,000 points of damage...to your heart.
column11:
Hab, loneliest zombie in the realm, is certain that this cactuar cutting was taken from his trusty companion Sabotendrick. Or if not, then most positively Sabotendred. What he does not know, is that it is, in fact, from the oft forgotten
Sabotendale.
column12:
The interior of its arm
holds a surprising amount
of fresh, drinkable water.
  - Common Knowledge

column10: Summon your smallshell minion. The mere sight of this wee wavekin may cause severe psychological trauma to those who spent years of their lives on faraway shores culling his relatives.
column11:
As is implied by its name, the smallshell's shell is small. What is not widely known is that unlike normal crabs whose shells grow thicker and, hence, larger as the crabs age, smallshell carapaces actually reduce in size due to erosion over the
wavekin's lifespan, until
nothing is left but legs.
column12:
Got naught but a sea
lion's share of crab offal
'twixt them ears, I reckon.
  - Ighii Moui

column10: Summon your wolf pup minion. Idolizes one Gaius van Baelsar for obvious reasons.
column11:
Bred to serve as a war wolf in the Imperial Garlean Army, this pup was rescued before any permanent damage could be done to its playful spirit. He will follow you to the end of the world and back...as
long as you toss him an
occasional biscuit.
column12:
I've got no words to mince
with whelps...unless you're
here to become a wolf.
  - Curious Gorge

column10: Summon your beady eye minion. That feeling you get sometimes that you are being watched? More often than not it is him.
column11: One of the most outlandish theories recently posed by scholars of the void is that ahrimans do not reproduce by typical sexual means, but rather by shedding tears which eventually grow into new creatures.
column12:
Black scorpion to sharpen
one's wit; ahriman
membrane for the mind.
  - Severian

column10: Summon your fledgling dodo minion. Properly trained not to eructate, regurgitate, expectorate, or flatulate.
column11:
Dodos mature extremely fast, going from fledgling to full-grown fryer in but a few short moons. This, coupled with the fact an adult female can lay up to seven eggs a sennight, makes this particular cloudkin the perfect option for
feeding the hungry masses.
column12:
Lightning Drools over the
Bismarck's Delightful
Grilled Dodo!
  - The Harbor Herald

column10: Summon your coblyn larva minion. Too dangerous to allow to grow any larger...too adorable to condemn to the furnace.
column11:
Coblyns will lay their eggs near ore deposits so that when the larvae emerge, they will have a ready supply of nourishment to form their protective outer carapaces. This is a slow process which involves dousing the ore in digestive
fluid, waiting for it to clarify,
then ingesting the ooze.
column12:
The lads go through gear
faster'n a coblyn chewin'
on a chunk of mythril.
  - Wawarukka

column10: Summon your wind-up aldgoat. No aldgoats were harmed in the making of this automaton.
column11:
While in Ishgardian folklore the aldgoat is used to represent greed and gluttony, the Dunesfolk believe the insatiable creatures are a symbol of wealth and prosperity, and will present aldgoat fetishes to families with newborn
children.
column12:
A nice big aldgoat steak
should put some color
back in 'er cheeks.
  - Lyngsath

column10: Summon your fledgling apkallu minion. Will follow you until you give him a fish. Will continue to follow you after being given a fish.
column11:
While the hatchlings of other flightless cloudkin have been observed covered in a dull brown coat of down when they emerge from their eggs, apkallus enter the world covered in the same vivid green plumage they will bear for their entire
lives.
column12:
Nesting hens do not spear
a failed egg thief a score
and a half times.
  - Frandelont Raimdelle

column10: Summon your goobbue sproutling minion. Has been known to attack kittens for no apparent reason.
column11:
To achieve their cyclopean size, goobbues must maintain a daily diet of several times their own weight. Luckily, the seedkin are not finicky eaters, and will consume almost anything that cannot outrun them. If rumors are to be
believed, this includes
Lalafells.
column12:
These goobbues are wont
to devour anything and
everything.
  - Aileen

column10: Summon your bite-sized pudding minion. Not intended for consumption.
column11:
Unable to reproduce, puddings increase their number solely via mitosis. Because of this, it is widely believed that all Eorzea's puddings descended from a single entity─a proto-pudding, if you will. This, however, leaves us with the question:
whence did the first
pudding come?
column12:
A talking...pudding?
  - You

column10: Summon your model vanguard minion. An exact 1:9 scale replica of a ceruleum-powered magitek vanguard (imperial pilot action figure not included).
column11:
Part of the Guildmaster Series, this high-quality replica is so exact in its rendition of the vanguard's build that Garlemald has banned the item's import into the empire's outlying provinces, for fear the data gleaned from it will be used by rebel
forces still active in these
lands.
column12:
I'd sooner face a vanguard
while naked as my
nameday!
  - Flame Private

column10: Summon your demon brick minion. We are all better off not knowing what arcane magicks animate this ordinary stone block.
column11:
For many years, modern archaeologists did not understand how a seemingly primitive civilization without clockwork or steam technology could build the massive stone structures of Amdapor. Animated bricks, such as the one that
has chosen to follow you,
may be the missing link.
column12:
Underneath this gear, I'm
built like a brick privy!
  - Chachai

column10: Summon your mini mole minion. When not dining on a protein-rich diet of earthworms and grubs, he dreams of making mountains.
column11:
Snatched from its hill while still young by infamous naturalist Marcette Manne, this poor creature has suffered countless experiments filled with endless pokings, proddings, potations, and panaceas. Compared to that, following
an adventurer around all
day is a veritable vacation.
column12:
Hear me, you mole
bastards? I am steel!
  - Eager Red Swallow

column10: Summon your tender lamb minion. Mint jelly optional.
column11:
As if predestined, your path crossed with that of the tender lamb's after she was brought to Eorzea from the dark reaches of the Far East by a hitsuji bugyo. Since then, you have been inseparable, the fluffy ball
of fleece following your
every footstep.
column12:
But everywhere the little
lambs went, lice were sure
to go.
  - Chartain

column10: Summon your slime puddle minion. Fun for the whole family.
column11:
Once stepped upon, slime can be nigh on impossible to remove from the soles of boots, making the shapeless creatures a nuisance to those who mine the mountains in which slimes reside. The <Emphasis>Encyclopedia Eorzea</Emphasis> recommends a
squeeze of sun lemon to
loosen their stony grip.
column12:
Silence the slimes, lest
you succumb to the
flames.
  - Ancient Proverb

column10: Summon your kidragora minion. Even in space, everyone can hear this seedkin scream.
column11: One must take care when harvesting mandragoras, for if the roots are disturbed they will emit a high-pitched scream powerful enough to shatter glass over a malm away.
column12:
While little is known about
them, what is known
tends to be disturbing.
  - Eorzean Naturalist

column10: Summon your wind-up goblin minion. Even this automaton's gobbiebag is bigger than yours.
column11: Designed to resemble goblin hero Brayflox Alltalks, you cannot help but wonder at the symbol carved into the sole of its left foot─the mark of the dreaded <Emphasis>Illuminati</Emphasis>.
column12:
<Emphasis>Illuminati</Emphasis> brainfruit
is frontmost!
  - <Emphasis>Illuminati</Emphasis> Member

column10: Summon your wind-up sylph minion. If it could speak, it would be in the third person.
column11:
Unlike most species in which the female bears the offspring, only sylph males are capable of reproduction, and they do so via the single flower found upon their heads. After the flower is fertilized, it will eventually fall off,
giving rise to a child
known as a podling.
column12:
Helping sylphs with their
problems is a jolly fine
way to make friends.
  - Path Companion

column10: Summon your wind-up cursor minion. Modeled after the ivory glove of Oschon, the Wanderer, does this clockwork hand follow you...or guide you?
column11:
If we are to believe the slurred ravings of a self-proclaimed goblin theologian deep in his cups, this seemingly inconspicuous white glove is actually the “Hand of Fate” by which all of us are controlled from a dimension beyond the
aether.
column12:
I trust ye had enough
fingers to help ye through
the tallyin'.
  - Yulgi Honalgi

column10: Summon your wind-up airship minion. A fully operational model of the legendary vessel, the <Emphasis>Invincible</Emphasis>.
column11:
Despite it being the first, and most ambitious undertaking by Highwind Skyways founder Tatanora, the <Emphasis>Invincible</Emphasis> actually never took flight─its ten-year construction period plagued by accidents, material shortages, sabotage, and
outright incompetence.
column12:
Up in the sky, look! It's a
bird─ No, it's an airship─
No! It's the inspector!
  - Nashu Mhakaracca

column10: Summon your wind-up Qiqirn minion. As adorable as the real thing, without the ratty odor.
column11:
Once upon a time, there was not a man, woman, or child in all of Limsa Lominsa who did not know the name Zazaroon, mummer extraordinaire. However, a taste for spiced rum, a failed marriage, and several run-ins with the Barracudas
saw the Qiqirn fall from
the limelight into oblivion.
column12:
The Qiqirn are a nuisance
at the best of times.
  - Roseline

column10: Summon your black chocobo chick minion. Rumors about her being able to fly are completely unfounded...or <Emphasis>are</Emphasis> they?
column11:
This poor chocobo chick was as yellow as an ear of millioncorn before one day being doused in black ink by a random passerby bedecked in silver accessories. Try as the chokobokeeps might, none were able to remove the taint, and thus
the realm's first black
chocobo was born.
column12:
There is no finer feel
than that of a chocobo
between your legs.
  - L'dhakya

column10: Summon your wind-up Dalamud minion. Do not attempt to pry open under any circumstances.
column11:
After Dalamud's fall, a wealthy Ul'dahn noble commissioned a famous troupe of musicians to write a dirge for the heroes of Carteneau and play it across Eorzea so that the deeds of the fallen would not be forgotten. This wind-up
model of the red moon has
naught to do with the dirge.
column12:
The lifeblood spilled in
Dalamud's name shall be
blessed upon His return.
  - Foxe

column10: Summon your minute mindflayer minion. Delights folk with its cuteness even as it fills them with an inexplicable sense of dread.
column11:
Similar to voidsent dullahan, mindflayers also lack a corporeal form and must possess a host to be able to exert force on our realm. Whereas the dullahan, however, are limited to the possession of inorganic objects such as steel,
mindflayers tend to prefer
the dead as their vessels.
column12:
It has a grisly penchant
for sucking out the brains
of men.
  - Frandelont Raimdelle

column10: Summon your tight-beaked parrot minion. For best results, summon while wearing an eyepatch.
column11: After witnessing the horrors experienced by his former master, Captain Madison, this once-outspoken oppo has gone silent, opening its beak only when offered a handful of sardines.
column12:
Parley! Parley!
Parley! Squaaawk!
  - Loose-beaked Parrot

column10: Summon your wind-up Amalj'aa minion. What is burnt may never burn, but rises again, harder and stronger.
column11:
Amalj'aa blacksmith Narujj Boh of the Brotherhood of Ash began dabbling in clockwork after rescuing the mammet minion of an adventurer slain near his forges. This particular sample is the product of moons of meticulous calculations
made to reproduce the
telltale Amalj'aa tail sway.
column12:
My people are the
Amalj'aa, proud and
strong.
  - Loonh Gah

column10: Summon your wind-up Ixal minion. He believes he can fly. He believes he can touch the sky. Unfortunately he cannot.
column11: Using a mammet obtained from the Goldsmiths' Guild by the ever-resourceful Tataramu, members of the Ehcatl Nine have succeeded in creating an automaton of their own...who also happens to be as grounded as their brethren.
column12:
I heard a Wood Wailer
telling Mummy that an
Ixal teared his face off.
  - Gridanian Child

column10: Summon your wind-up kobold minion. With you, she will koboldly go where no kobold has gone before.
column11: Another of 789th Order Acolyte Ba Go's masterpieces, this cuddly kobold miniature in fact houses several onzes of highly flammable firesand, designed to ignite when outward pressure is applied...such as with a tender hug.
column12:
Honestly, I will never
understand the kobolds'
sense of aesthetics.
  - Rashaht

column10: Summon your wind-up Sahagin minion. He's got a trident and he's not afraid to use it.
column11: Ever the loving clutchfather, Novv had this toy crafted, complete with sharpened trident, for his infant spawnlings. When wound up, it displays various thrusts and parries to prepare the spawn for battle with their enemies.
column12:
A Sssahagin does not flail
and sssplash about so─
he rolls with the waves.
  - Clutchfather Novv

column10: Summon your wind-up brickman minion. The brickman gets up and looks over as if it wants to join the party!
column11:
One unexpected side effect of the Calamity has been the significant increase in aetherial rifts appearing throughout the realm. As a result, strange creatures not of this world have been popping in and out of existence without warning─
one of those being the
bizarre brickman.
column12:
Can ye smell it?
'Tis the scent o' profit,
my friend!
  - Beefy Businessman

column10:
Summon your wind-up Shantotto minion. But remember:
If you fail to treat her right,
she will set your pants alight.
column11: If it looks like a Lalafell, rhymes like a Lalafell, and alliterates like a Lalafell, then it is probably a Lalafell...except when it is a wind-up Shantotto. Then it is not a Lalafell.
column12:
Your judgment is quite
wise─you may yet stave
off an untimely demise.
  - Shantotto

column10: Summon your wind-up Edvya minion. Sometimes moonlights as a miller girl, much to her father the sultan's chagrin.
column11:
Forty years after the founding of the Thorne Dynasty, sultan Baldric Thorne was blessed by the gods with a single daughter, Edvya, whom he loved fiercely. The history surrounding the two, now known as the “Legend of the Lost Lady”
gave rise to the festival
of Little Ladies' Day.
column12:
Did Princess Edvya
concern herself with glory
and riches? I think not!
  - Gossiping Girl

column10: Summon your wind-up sun minion. May the sun never go down on you.  /poke to adjust elevation.
column11:
Designed to provide light for road repairmen toiling during the small hours of the night, wind-up suns have become all the talk amongst Ul'dahn mesdames ever since it was discovered the extra light worked wonders at hiding unsightly
blemishes and wrinkles.
column12:
We find the pages of our
memories are blank, as if
bleached by the sun.
  - Kan-E-Senna

column10: Summon your plush cushion minion. Ever ready to shield your buttocks from the hardest of places.
column11:
Preferring to take a more hands-on approach with his latest project, Redolent Rose of the Weavers' Guild personally researched the resilience and contour of over four score buttocks in order to create a cushion so light and fluffy, even
the clouds would darken
with envy.
column12:
Bumbling one spends all
day sleeping on
paperstack pillow, yes?
  - Olmxio

column10: Summon your Minion of Light and make true the prophecy: “When Darkness veils the world, three Minions of Light shall come.”
column11:
Ancient records show that almost every Astral Era has had its own Warriors of Light─brave souls who appeared before forthcoming disasters to unite the people of that time...only to disappear once again as catastrophe rained down
from the heavens.
column12:
Next you'll be telling me
you're one of the Warriors
of Light.
  - Mother Miounne

column11:
Ancient records show that almost every Astral Era has had its own Warriors of Light─brave souls who appeared before forthcoming disasters to unite the people of that time...only to disappear once again as catastrophe rained down
from the heavens.
column12:
Next you'll be telling me
you're one of the Warriors
of Light.
  - Mother Miounne

column11:
Ancient records show that almost every Astral Era has had its own Warriors of Light─brave souls who appeared before forthcoming disasters to unite the people of that time...only to disappear once again as catastrophe rained down
from the heavens.
column12:
Next you'll be telling me
you're one of the Warriors
of Light.
  - Mother Miounne

column11:
Ancient records show that almost every Astral Era has had its own Warriors of Light─brave souls who appeared before forthcoming disasters to unite the people of that time...only to disappear once again as catastrophe rained down
from the heavens.
column12:
Next you'll be telling me
you're one of the Warriors
of Light.
  - Mother Miounne

column10: Summon your wind-up leader minion, who will follow you unquestioningly─for coin and country; for serenity, purity, sanctity─till sea swallows all.
column11:
Originally crafted to promote the Grand Companies of Eorzea, these clockwork dolls are often rewarded to company members for exceptional service. There are three models of wind-up leaders, one to represent
each of the three heads of
Limsa Lominsa, Gridania,
and Ul'dah.
column12:
The leaders of Eorzea had
lost their way─I merely
helped them find it again.
  - Minfilia

column11:
Originally crafted to promote the Grand Companies of Eorzea, these clockwork dolls are often rewarded to company members for exceptional service. There are three models of wind-up leaders, one to represent
each of the three heads of
Limsa Lominsa, Gridania,
and Ul'dah.
column12:
The leaders of Eorzea had
lost their way─I merely
helped them find it again.
  - Minfilia

column11:
Originally crafted to promote the Grand Companies of Eorzea, these clockwork dolls are often rewarded to company members for exceptional service. There are three models of wind-up leaders, one to represent
each of the three heads of
Limsa Lominsa, Gridania,
and Ul'dah.
column12:
The leaders of Eorzea had
lost their way─I merely
helped them find it again.
  - Minfilia

column11:
Originally crafted to promote the Grand Companies of Eorzea, these clockwork dolls are often rewarded to company members for exceptional service. There are three models of wind-up leaders, one to represent
each of the three heads of
Limsa Lominsa, Gridania,
and Ul'dah.
column12:
The leaders of Eorzea had
lost their way─I merely
helped them find it again.
  - Minfilia

column10: Summon the princely hatchling minion, the chocobo who would be king.
column11: A thoroughbred descended from the legendary Veillantif, this noble bird of Ishgard seeks a rider who will not sully his family's name.
column12:
I had a feeling you'd be
riding up on your golden
chocobo.
  - Path Companion

column10: Summon your wind-up Odin minion. Guaranteed not to wipe out your entire party in one fell stroke.
column11:
Many have pondered why a dark divinity with roots in northern mythology would wield a blade with a decidedly Far Eastern name. A popular theory is that Odin acquired the blade upon slaying an Auri warrior who was the first ever
to notch his thereto-
fore unsullied plate.
column12:
If Odin is truly come to
the Shroud, time is not on
our side.
  - Lewin

column10:
Summon your wind-up Warrior of Light minion.
“Wheresoever thou goest, so too shall Light follow.”
─Ancient benediction
column11: The brilliant blue suit of armor worn by the wind-up Warrior of Light is based upon ancient Allagan designs rediscovered in recent years by adventurers returned from the Crystal Tower.
column12:
There will be no Warriors
of Light to save you this
time.
  - Gaius van Baelsar

column10: Summon your wind-up Bahamut minion. This mysterious being emerged from within a broken wind-up Dalamud, and is nigh inseparable from its former prison.
column11:
Despite strict orders from the Goldsmiths' Guild to <Emphasis>never</Emphasis> open up the Dalamud minion under any circumstances, someone decided to unleash their inner Pandora and release the terrors hidden within─a wind-up Bahamut...which
no one from the guild
recalls creating!
column12:
Bahamut can't live on 
good wishes and a smile,
so why should I?
  - Flame Private

column10: Summon your wind-up moogle minion. With its button nose and fluffy pom, this clockwork moogle will make you the envy of all your friends.
column11:
A creation born of 90% love and 10% jealousy (or was that 90% jealousy and 10% love?), this clockwork masterpiece was conceived after the moogles of the Black Shroud began noticing all the adventurers with their new shiny minions,
and decided they were
not about to be left out.
column12:
What the moogles lack in
grace, they amply make
up for in wit.
  - Jehantel

column10: Summon your baby opo-opo minion. The only thing it loves more than you is a juicy sprite apple.
column11:
A daring rescue from the clutches of the goblin hero Brayflox's minions is the only thing separating this opo-opo from a life of swinging free from tree to tree through the lush jungles of the Longstop...and forever trudging in the wake of the
brave adventurer who
“saved” him.
column12:
These beans are covered
in opo-opo droppings!
  - Mun–Tuy Cellarkeep

column10: Summon your magic broom minion. For safety reasons, do not fall asleep while it is at work.
column11:
While you may not hear many of the realm's mages admit it, magicking a household broom to become a self-propelled sweeping servitor (albeit one which does very little actual cleaning) is far more complicated than it sounds,
requiring no fewer than
seven cants of binding.
column12:
A lancer who fears to
attack is naught but a
man holding a pole.
  - Ywain

column10: Summon your wind-up succubus minion. 100% anatomically correct. Handle with tender loving care.
column11:
One of countless clockwork servitors discovered in the home of a Gridanian goldsmith recently hanged for the crime of ritual summoning. It is believed while crafting the automatons, he became increasingly obsessed with the void,
until the darkness bid
him do the unthinkable.
column12:
That succubus will drain
you to a lifeless husk!
  - Cocobygo

column10: Summon your zu hatchling. This newborn zu has yet to exhibit aggressive or territorial behavior, but when it gets bigger...
column11:
While native to the scorching deserts of the Near East, the zu will migrate to a cooler Eorzea after hatching its fledglings in the spring. Since the Calamity, however, there have been an increasing number of
cases where the giant
cloudkin remain in
Eorzea year-round.
column12:
These birds move slow,
but they've a nasty peck!
  - Jacke

column10: Summon your wind-up Nanamo minion. She vehemently refuses to sit upon any shoulder but Raubahn's...and yours.
column11: This clockwork doll is a reproduction of a model first crafted in the year of the Calamity to celebrate the tenth anniversary of Nanamo Ul Namo's ascendance to the Ul'dahn throne. Seventeenth in her line, the sultana was crowned when she had seen but five summers.
column12:
Take me, Raubahn... I am
your sultana... <snore>
   - Slumbering Lalafell

column10: Summon your Gilgamesh minion. Several arms appear to be missing, but that does not seem to otherwise hinder basic functionality.
column11:
The masterwork of one of Eorzea's finest goldsmiths, this wind-up automaton, designed to resemble a close acquaintance of the smith's son, was pieced together using parts left over from other projects─his only regret being that he was
unable to incorporate
hip-gyrating functionality.
column12:
For Gilgamesh... It is
embiggening time!
  - Gilgamesh

column10: Summon your Onion Prince minion. He would die 4 U. Or possibly cry 4 U. Or most likely make U cry. 4 U.
column11: After learning his parents married not for love, but for duty, the Onion Prince vowed he would never walk in the footsteps of his parents, and to this day promises his baseborn sweetheart, the Leek Maid, that they will run away and be wed.
column12:
Aw, bloody hells! Who's
cutting onions back
there!?
  - Buscarron

column10: Summon your Eggplant Knight minion. His childhood dream to become a wizard was frowned upon by his overbearing father.
column11: House Eggplant has faithfully served the royal line of Tomato kings for eighteen generations, never once betraying the throne...until, that is, the knight of the nineteenth generation laid eyes on the fair Mandragora Queen.
column12:
If you eat too many of
this vegetable, you will
turn into one.
  - Common Wives' Tale

column10: Summon your Garlic Jester minion. Every breath you take will act as a reminder that your pungent pal is right behind you.
column11:
The son of a traveling mummer who performed under the name Garlic Star, the jester swore he would never follow in the footsteps of his father. However, after being deemed too malodorous to serve in the royal guard, he swallowed
his pride and fell back on
the only trade he knew.
column12:
And this irresistible
aroma... Mmmmmmmmm...
  - Ingham

column10: Summon your King Tomato minion. Has issued a royal decree for the public defenestration of any and all who mistakenly claim the king is a vegetable.
column11:
After the flames of the Calamity rendered Lord Tomato a king without a kingdom, the ruby red regent packed up his seeds and set out on a journey to find a new land to rule. He currently roams the realm recruiting any taproot,
tuber, or corm who
will follow his standard.
column12:
It is apparently a rogue,
outcast from its kin, a
stranger in a strange land.
  - Tomaj

column10: Though wed to the Tomato King in a move to strengthen the bond of Houses Tomato and Mandragora, the queen longs to steal away with her one true love─the Eggplant Knight. What will become of this forbidden romance!? Summon the Mandragora Queen minion today and find out!
column11: Destined to a life with a man she did not love, nary a night passed when the Mandragora Queen did not dream of throwing herself into the sea's eternal embrace...until, that is, she laid eyes on the noble Eggplant Knight.
column12:
I want to be waist-deep
in little white mandragora
limbs!
  - Yellowjacket

column10: Summon your wind-up Y'shtola. If we are to take her word for it, the Circle of Knowing Archon has seen but twenty-three summers.
column11:
Nearly half of the coin provided to the Goldsmiths' Guild for the crafting of this wind-up doll bearing the likeness of Scion of the Seventh Dawn Y'shtola was paid to Atelier Fen-Yll for hand-sewn leather boots matching those worn by
the enigmatic Archon.
column12:
Gods forfend...
   - Y'shtola

column10: Summon your magic wind-up onion knight minion. An accurate representation of the soldiers who once made up the greater portion of the Allagan Imperial Army.
column11:
If Sons of Saint Coinach anthropogeographer Rammbroes is to be believed, towards the end of their civilization, the Allagans began using automatons such as this to fight their wars (which had been deemed inhumane, yet
ultimately necessary to
spread imperial peace).
column12:
By the Onion!
  - Bloezoeng

column10: Summon your treasure box minion. It is unknown what manner of spirit possesses this tiny treasure chest, but the fact that it will not hesitate to nip at the fingers of any who try and pry it open is painfully evident.
column11:
Originally used by an Eorzean Alliance paymaster to store Allied Seals...until the box began eating them. She sold the box in hopes of recouping some of her losses (skimming off adventurer rewards to cover the rest...until she was
caught and sentenced
to a public flogging).
column12:
A pirate don't abandon
'is treasures!
  - Ahtzapfyn

column10: Summon your tiny tapir minion. Natives of the New World claim that tapirs grow by devouring the dreams of their unsuspecting owners. And now you know what to expect.
column11:
Before it was realized that the tapirs were, in fact, consuming the dreams of their owners, several hundred were sold to Ul'dahn nobles seeking a better night's sleep. Surprisingly, there were few complaints
from buyers, even after
learning the truth.
column12:
Our dreams are
what sustain us.
  - Gundobald

column10: Summon your bear cub minion. Pundits claim bears to be the deadliest beasts in the realm─obviously having never stared into <Emphasis>this</Emphasis> cute cub's nebulous eyes.
column11:
The Nana bear's origins can be traced back to Ul'dahn princess Nanakko who, on her eighth nameday, asked her father for a bear. Despite a realm-wide search, no bears were found, and so the Goldsmiths' Guild was commissioned to craft
one from a drawing found
in an ancient bestiary.
column12:
There isn't enough honey
in all the Yard to satisfy
that sweet-toothed sellary.
  - Honey Yard Hivekeep

column10: Summon your miniature minecart minion. Best when ridden in abandoned mines and temples of doom.
column11:
Despite adamant claims by Amajina & Sons Mineral Concern that their donation of over five score carts to the orphans of Stonesthrow was a simple act of charity, opponents of the guild insist it was a scheme to recruit inexpensive
child labor for Thanalan's
myriad mines.
column12:
Mines mine!
Mines all miiiiiiiiine!
  - Biggy the Spriggan

column10: Summon your nutkin minion. That nutkins are infamous for being shy and timid creatures shows that this brave beastkin comes complete with a pair of iron acorns on him.
column11: Inspired by the words of Millith Ironheart, this daring squirrel longs to travel the realm in search of the legendary golden acorn, and hopes that trailing in your shadow will ensure that he isn't eaten before he discovers the mother lode.
column12:
I had no idea squirrels
could bite so hard!
  - Arold

column10: Summon your wind-up Minfilia minion. Unlike the real Minfilia, this one actually accompanies you on your adventures.
column11:
This clockwork automaton has been crafted at the behest of the Adventurers' Guild in celebration of the Rising, Eorzea's annual celebration of rebirth. All linkshell privileges have been revoked so one not need dread incessant
calls throughout the
small hours of night.
column12:
...Hello? Hello? Can you
hear me? It is I, Minfilia.
  - Minfilia

column10: Summon your wind-up Thancred minion. 200% more dreamy than previous models.
column11:
This clockwork automaton has been crafted at the behest of the Adventurers' Guild in celebration of the Rising, Eorzea's annual celebration of rebirth. Reports of crazed Thancred fans stalking the summoned servitors are more
common than one
might believe.
column12:
I suppose any name is as
good as another, though
most call me Thancred.
  - Thancred

column10: Summon your model magitek bit minion. An exact 1:9 scale replica of a ceruleum-powered magitek bit (Ultima Weapon action figure not included).
column11: This miracle of modern mechanics is actually a miracle of ancient Allagan mechanics reverse engineered and then modified with advanced Garlean magitek technology.
column12:
The Empire owes
its might to magitek.  - Yda

column10: Summon your puff of darkness minion. When standing nearby, prithee refrain from coughing, sneezing, waving, flailing, or performing any other means of wild gesticulation, lest the puff be lost for eternity.
column11:
When this automaton resembling one crafted by a goldsmith hanged for dabbling in the dark arts was discovered, it prompted authorities to exhume the recently buried body. This, however, only confirmed
their worst fears─
that the coffin was
empty.
column12:
What I do not smother,
I devour. What I cannot
devour, I destroy.
  - The Cloud of Darkness

column10: Summon your naughty nanka minion. Like its parent, the ninki nanka, this slippery wavekin will breed like a rabbit if left unsupervised.
column11:
Instead of laying her eggs in a pond or river where they might be devoured by predators, the ninki nanka female deposits her offspring upon the back of the father, who then carries and protects the brood until it is ready to face the world
on its own. Unless,
however, one falls off.
column12:
Shiiiiiiny! Preeeeeetty!
Need more eeeeeeggs!
Eeeeeeggs!
  - Giggity the Spriggan

column10: Summon your wind-up Ultros minion.
column11: One can only imagine the time and effort master goldsmith Godbert put into the creation of this lifelike recreation of a lecherous purple octopus.
column12:
Muscle heads? Hate 'em!
  - Ultros

column10: Summon your Hoary the Snowman minion. Hoary the Snowman was a jolly happy soul, without a pipe, and without a nose, and two eyes made out of something other than coal. Probably slag.
column11:
While no one knows the exact origins of Hoary the Snowman and the legends surrounding this animated mass of ice and snow, the gifting of dolls created in his likeness to good girls and boys is not uncommon during the Starlight
Celebration.
column12:
On your feet, Hoary!
  - Coultenet

column10: Summon your heavy hatchling minion. Currently, “baby fat” is the prevailing excuse for this cherubic chick's gigant-like girth.
column11:
It would be foolish to believe that a chocobo could achieve this size dining on greens alone, regardless of how many hundreds of bushels were devoured...in a single sitting. Chicken bones found beneath the chick's bedding suggest
he may have a taste
for his succulent cousins.
column12:
I cannot deny what you say is
true any more than I can deny
a chocobo's arse is yellow.
  - Path Companion

column10: Summon your wind-up Yda minion. Comes complete with irremovable mask.
column11:
Due to her apparent lack of wit and tendency to be in the wrong place at the wrong time, people are quick to forget that Yda is not only a Scion of the Seventh Dawn, but also an Archon of the Circle of Knowing, hand-picked by the
legendary Louisoix
to serve Eorzea.
column12:
The great beyond!
I do believe we're
dead, Papalymo.
   - Yda

column10: Summon your wind-up Papalymo minion. Comes complete with irremovable smirk.
column11:
After a clerical error resulted in a sizable windfall for the organization, Scions of the Seventh Dawn coinkeeper Tataru took it upon herself to use the funds to commission wind-up automatons crafted in the likeness of her
own favorite members─
Papalymo being the first.
column12:
He'd sooner swallow
his staff than admit
that he's wrong.
   - Yda

column10: Summon your wind-up Urianger minion. When the septenary moon did wane, there sounded a garrulous and convoluted monologue. A new minion had roused, one whose identity lieth within our ken.
column11:
After commissioning six other wind-up Archons, the Scions of the Seventh Dawn coinkeeper realized that she had almost enough gil to order a seventh...almost. And so the robed and hooded Urianger was crafted without hair or other
anatomical features to
keep the cost down.
column12:
Frustratingly, Urianger's
words leave rather a lot
to interpretation.
   - Papalymo

column10: Summon your fat cat minion. Despite convincing research by top academics from around the realm and beyond, most Miqo'te scholars refuse to believe that there may be some ancestral connection between their race and cats (fat or not).
column11:
Born in an unmarked alley in an unnamed town, this poor creature had to hunt the mean streets just to stay alive...until learning that following retainers and feeding off the slaughter left in their wakes was a safer, easier way to
a full belly.
column12:
When the master's away,
the cat will play.
  - Miqo'te Retainer

column10: Summon your Littlefoot minion. This particular Yeti is content in knowing that bigger is not always necessarily better.
column11:
When discovered by your retainer on a foray deep into the highlands of Coerthas, this miniature monstrosity was both cold and hungry (though the former condition most likely did not affect him much), and a bowl of hot broth was
all it took to lure him
from the forest back home.
column12:
It is good to see you
on your feet again.
  - Merlwyb Bloefhyswyn

column10: Summon your mummy's little mummy minion. While as cute as a button, remember, mummies are ultimately embalmed corpses damned to eternal thralldom in the land of the living. Have fun.
column11:
It is believed that the ancient technique of mummification─which involved embalming, organ removal, wrapping, and the burial in a multi-layered sarcophagus─was an expensive undertaking. That it was performed on a
child can attest to
his parents' devotion.
column12:
I told you, I'm
<Emphasis>not</Emphasis> your mummy!
  - Ul'dahn Citizen

column10: Summon your model <Emphasis>Enterprise</Emphasis> minion. Designed to boldly go where you have gone before.
column11:
The original <Emphasis>Enterprise</Emphasis> was designed and built while Garlond family prodigy Cid was still working as a military engineer for the Garlean Empire. The aft crane─intended for the loading of imperial
weaponry─was added to
the airship in the days
before Cid's defection.
column12:
<Emphasis>Enterprise</Emphasis>, engage!
   - Alphinaud

column10: Summon your wind-up delivery moogle minion. For when you absolutely, positively require moogle accompaniment.
column11:
The never-ending flow of adventurers into Eorzea has placed quite a burden on the realm's little letter-carriers. To help lighten their load, several acolytes at the Goldsmiths' Guild volunteered their time to create a veritable army of
miniature mail moogles.
column12:
Behold, for I shall now
perform for you the moogle
dance of inimitable integrity!
   - Delivery Moogle

column10: Summon your assassin fry minion. There was an old betta who swallowed a fry. No one knows why it swallowed the fry, but for some reason, the fry can now fly.
column11:
After several turns of the sun sloshing about in the depths of a ninja betta's belly, this freshly hatched fry has given up swimming altogether and taken to the skies. How spending time in a belly can inspire a fish to flight is something only
one who has spent time
in a belly can know.
column12:
They say never to look
a gift fish in the mouth.
  - Sisipu

column10: Summon your demon box minion. There is no better way to tell a special someone “thank you for attending my Ceremony of Eternal Bonding” than by giving them a sentient box that may or may not devour their pets.
column11:
Lacking the spells required to animate a gift in the same manner in which the ancients animated bricks, the crafter of this quaint creation simply cut a pair of holes into a wooden box and slipped it on a spriggan.
Problem solved.
column12:
That Miqo'te lass said
someone'd be bringin' me a
gift what I couldn't refuse.
  - Drogo

column10: Summon your water imp minion. Legend states these strange creatures can only survive on land as long as the plate atop their heads remains wet.
column11:
Even a child knows that there are no such things as water imps...but if that is true, then what in the world could this undeniably imp-like creature be? An undocumented species of gigantoad/salamander hybrid? Or perhaps simply
the hapless victim of a
misdirected Imp spell?
column12:
Not <Emphasis>more</Emphasis> imps!
They'll have all our honey!
  - Befuddled Beekeeper

column10: Summon your wind-up Louisoix minion. The Seventh Astral Era is secure as long as the Archon is ever at our sides.
column11:
When asked why the Goldsmiths' Guild began manufacture of the wind-up delivery moogles before even drawing up designs for their wind-up Louisoix─the single greatest hero in the history of history─Guildmaster Serendipity
replied, “Moogles are
cuter.”
column12:
I swear by Louisoix's beard,
I'll tear the skin from his─
  - Geva

column10: Summon Midgardsormr. Not the big one. The little one.
column11:
Father of Dragons, Keeper of the Lake, Bane of the XIVth Legion─while it is difficult to believe the yalm-long pup could be any of these things, he assures you his current form is only temporary while he awaits the reconstruction of a new
corporeal vessel.
column12:
Midgardsormr was a king
amongst kings who reigned
for centuries on end...
  - Minfilia

column10: Summon your Enkidu minion. That green is not coming out, even with multiple washings.
column11:
Legend has that Gilgamesh first found Enkidu while searching for a meal. Without the means to make a fire, he attempted to eat the fowl raw, only to find himself the victim of a furious counterattack. Impressed by the bird's
tenacity, he promptly
made her his pet.
column12:
Enkidu, do you hear me!?
ENKIIIDUUUUUUUUUUUU!
  - Gilgamesh

column10: Summon your wind-up Violet minion. Touched by a primal and corrupted to the core...yet adorable nonetheless.
column11: After being harried by their hostile sylvan cousins one time too many, the sylphs of Little Solace turned to a traveling goldsmith from faraway Ul'dah to help them create an automated decoy that might keep the touched ones away.
column12:
This one is in the mood for
dancing! And prancing!
  - Hostile Sylph

column10: Summon your wind-up founder minion. Four score and many more years ago, the Amalj'aa founding fathers dreamed of a day when in their footsteps would walk adorable minions. That day has finally come.
column11:
Amalj'aa legend tells of Whiteknuckle Kerigg Roh─undefeated on the battlefield, he is a hero to many, including Warleader Hamujj Gah. The champion is also father of the brawling style of martial arts utilized by the beast tribe to
this day.
column12:
Do you know, honored ally,
what is most distasteful to
the Amalj'aa?
  - Narujj Boh

column10: Summon your wind-up Dezul Qualan minion. It is said Ixali engineer Dezul Qualan began crafting war dirigibles after having a vision of ninety-nine red balloons floating over the Black Shroud.
column11:
The last time Ixali engineer Dezul Qualan was seen was the day he boarded his greatest creation─a war balloon thrice the size of any ever built, and equipped with enough provisions to last a man a full moon in the clouds. His destination:
the floating continent
of Ayatlan.
column12:
Soar once again, we shall.
Within <Emphasis>Dezul Qualan</Emphasis>,
our salvation lies!
  - Sezul Totoloc

column10: Summon your wind-up kobolder minion. Bolder than a wind-up kobold, yet not any older.
column11:
Unsatisfied with the explosive power of his first creation, 789th Order Acolyte Ba Go returned to his laboratories deep within the faction dig to create the “kobolder” (a name he was quite pleased with), only to see it sold for scrap
by his dim-witted brethren.
column12:
Doings of small minds
and grubby hands are
of no interest to Ba Go.
  - Ba Go

column10: Summon your wind-up Sea Devil minion. A clockwork automaton expertly crafted to resemble the infamous Scarlet Sea Devil, leader of the Coral Tridents.
column11:
Ever the loving clutchfather, Novv had this toy crafted, complete with blood-red accents, for his infant spawnlings. When wound up, it displays the ferocity and cunning that was the clutch's first patriarch─the
Scarlet Sea Devil.
column12:
The white coral necklace
he wore was stained
perpetually red with blood.
  - Ururu Kogururu
